  <h1 class="article__title reveal">Designing with AI: Where UX Meets Machine Learning</h1>

  <p class="reveal">
    The conversation around AI in design often focuses on tools — which AI can generate
    layouts, write copy, or produce images. But the more interesting question is about
    the experiences themselves: how do we design interactions with AI that feel natural,
    trustworthy, and genuinely useful?
  </p>

  <p class="reveal">
    As interaction designers, we have a unique responsibility in this space. We're the ones
    shaping how people experience these powerful systems. And that means thinking beyond
    the interface to the underlying mental models, expectations, and emotional responses
    that AI-powered products create.
  </p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The Design Challenge of Uncertainty</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    Traditional interfaces are deterministic — press a button, get a predictable result.
    AI introduces probabilistic outcomes, and that fundamentally changes the design contract
    with users. How do you design for a system that might be wrong? How do you build trust
    when outputs vary?
  </p>

  <blockquote class="reveal">
    The best AI experiences don't hide the machine — they create a transparent partnership
    between human judgment and computational capability.
  </blockquote>

  <h2 class="reveal">What Interaction Designers Bring to the Table</h2>

  <p class="reveal">
    Our training in user research, information architecture, and interaction patterns is
    exactly what AI products need. We know how to ask the right questions about user needs,
    how to structure complex information clearly, and how to design feedback loops that
    help people understand and control the systems they use.
  </p>

